segments.text: You might have a date that would be coming in on the train from Dallas, Fort Worth.
And as I recall, there was an evening train about 5 o'clock that they could catch and come down.
You'd meet them at the station.
you know, take them to their room, whatever facilities that, you know, they had.
They had dorms open sometimes, or they could stay at a house, you know.
And lots of times they would come down and they would stay with somebody, some other local girl who lived here.
And then you would line up for the dance.
and little activities.
We used to go after the dance to a little kind of party afterwards at the old country club building at the Bryan Municipal Lake.
That was a favorite place.
You know, you could rent that and meet there after the dance, you know, to go all night, you see.
And that was something that you could do.
Now, generally, these girls came from where?
From TSCW or from SMU or any other school.
Who paid their railroad?
They would do that.
Okay.
And how were these young women treated once they arrived in College Station?
Well, they, it all depends upon which
how you were classified.
If you were a freshman bringing a girl, well, you knew that she wasn't looking at you, she was looking at the upperclassmen.
And that was the way it went.
Now, if you were a senior, well, you were looking at other girls that somebody else had brought, you see.
But then again, your own date, and lots of them by that time were...
were what we would call senior favorites, you know, that the Longhorns called senior favorites, and they had known each other for a while.
And that was a little different.
Then senior ring dance was a little special, too, you see.
I had one answer when I asked how were they treated, and he said, like royalty.
Well, that's true.
But you know, I remember once there was a, and you might know this school there in Missouri, Stevens.
Oh, yes.
Stevens College.
Stevens College.
As they would take tours, those girls, and one of their trains happened to land at College Station once.
Really?
for a very quick dance and getting back on.
I just know that they had a hard time getting them all on the train to leave.
Was this while you were a student?
I don't think I was either.
I don't think I was a student.
I may have been, but I didn't know any of our mediums.
Stevens College was then a two-year institution on the east end of Broadway in downtown Columbia, Missouri, and had a high reputation as a finishing school for southern ladies.
Correct.
And they...
were supposedly, if they went to Stevens, supposedly they came from a prestigious family and so forth.
And I'm smiling at the potential combination
of the Aggie energy and the Stevens girls.
Let's see, the student indulgences of that time, tobacco and alcohol and did undergraduate smoke much then?
I don't, they did but I don't think they,
did to an excess.
Of course, you had some smokers.
What were the favorite brands?
Lucky Strike, you know, and then Lucky Strike goes to... Lucky Strike Green.
Lucky Strike Green goes to war, something like that.
Chesterfield, I guess, as I faintly recall.
But, you know, we didn't have any kind of...
That was the extent of it.
Indulgence would be tobacco and alcohol.
I don't think I ever know of anything else besides that.
Did you hear of anybody going to the chicken ranch in LaGrange?
Did you know it existed?
We knew it existed, but I think the recent story about the Junction Boys put it more on the map than it was because they had a local
establishment closer than the chicken ranch, it was over here at Brenham.
I had never heard of that.
Now, I have never heard any mention of a bootlegger in Brazos County that is a place to buy illegal whiskey.
No, I don't know of any.
Come to think of it, I don't know if we had any.
I'm not heard of them.
Well, wait a minute now.
Let's just say probably some of these guys could have gone to what we called at that time North Bryan.
and might have been able to obtain something.
I don't think it was a habit.
And I've not heard of anyone mention a house of ill repute in Bryan College Station.
No, not in those times.
The only one that I recall or heard about was the one at Brenham.
After World War II, near the end of it, I heard of
some rumors about activities on the other side of the Brazos River Bridge just beyond the air base.

that there were two or three places apparent but that was not for a case that was for for the air base that uh... a little bit gambling and goodness knows what else in the background well uh... it could have been could have been uh... back to uh... backed a m uh... silver caps was that a reality during your days earlier do you remember it was it was it was very special and it was all different uh...
key than it is today.
It was done at academic, and lights were off, and it wasn't publicized
Anything like that.
It was usually on an individual basis.
Did everyone take it seriously?
Oh, yeah.
Absolutely.
And it was quite an occasion.
But, you know, it's just like, well, we go back to the muster and all, you see.
They do so much about that now.

Midnight yell practice that was good in the old days because it was unscheduled It would came at a time that the yell leader thought that we needed to boost the team a little bit and All of a sudden it would happen There was a lot of toilet paper thrown And it wasn't scheduled before every home game did it occur in the stadium in
No, sir.
It occurred usually when Yale practice was on the steps of the YMCA.
That's what I thought.
And then later moved to the steps of Goodwin Hall.
But of course, it wasn't a production.
As you were preparing to leave for graduation, what did you and your classmates, what were you all talking about?
I think I can guess.
We were really
concerned about what was going to happen to us as far as whether we were going to be enlisted or whether we were going to be sent to officer candidate school.
And as I recall, we went to Houston and were inducted as enlisted men in the reserve and then
called to active duty and we all then went to, well, not everybody, but most of us went to Fort Sam Houston and were inducted.
And this was a little unusual.
Before you could go to OCS, you had to be a corporal.
So here we were reporting in as privates and then in a week being promoted to corporal,
sent to OCS.
While the rest of the guys when we got to OCS were sergeants and corporals for more months than we were.
When did you get your Aggie ring?
Do you remember?
You have to have so many hours.
What was it, 100 or 90 hours?
That's what it used to be.
90 hours, I think, something like that.
And you brought it through the registrar.
Remember what it cost?
$23.75, something like that.
Do you have any special Aggie Ring stories to share?
Where you lost it or somebody recognized it when you walked into a certain building or something or other?
No, I really don't, but it's recognized all over.
Is that your original?
That's my original, pretty well worn.
When you left to go to World War II, how well prepared and trained did you and your colleagues think you were?
We thought we were ready, you know, actually.
But the little daily exercise that was part of our routine on our senior year really didn't.
prepare you, because we didn't know what the armor was like.
But we soon found out.
We're getting near the end of the questions that I had thought about.
Can you think of any important omissions so far, some special things you wanted to be sure to include?
I won't probably think about that until after you've gone.
Okay.
But there's so many things that you just can't recall.
Oh, yes.
What are the key ingredients of Aggie spirit?
What creates that feeling?
Well, I think it's association with...
men and women now that you have so much in common and you live it and you go away and you still live it and you're just a part of it.
It's really
Of course, under the new logo they've got for the former Students Association, the ring is the thing, but that's just representative of what it's all.
They've had so many, and they go through, I think, at A&M a lot of, and it's on a different scale, but when I was in A&M, you had so many
associations, though however small, they were all based on the common contact that you had and the goal that you had to finish and be some kind of a citizen, you see.
Am I correct that for you and your contemporaries, it didn't matter very much about how much family income that youngster had in his background, what his hometown was?
It's what he did when he got here and how he reacted thereafter.
And to me, there were and hopefully still are a series of activities that were inclusive in nature of Aggies instead of being exclusive.
That's right.
That's a good way to say it.
Once an A&M man, always...
That's what makes it.
The, for example, when you were a student, I'm assuming that it didn't, that you had some acquaintances who were Hispanic, who were Jewish, who were Catholic, who were Protestant.
Yes, and maybe I ought not to make a record of this, but you know,
When I was going to A&M, we had no blacks.
That was an old saying, you know, where the Prairie View students
picked up an Aggie, or they had something in Canada, and they ended up, they said, well, us Aggies has got to stick together.
But I don't, we didn't, you took the guy as he came from whatever source.
I went to high school in Orange.
And I heard about the Kishi boys that came to A&M.
Were any of the Kishi boys here when you were here?
They were Japanese?
Japanese?
Mm-hmm.
No, I don't think so.
But were they horticulturalists?
Mm-hmm.
Mm-hmm.
Their family had been, originally they were rice farmers that came early in the century, and so they were second generation American, and all fought in Europe.
I don't remember that family.
The biggest family that I can recall of A&M
students from Beaumont, the Kokinos.
Yes.
Mike was in my class.
Let me record an anecdote about the Kokinos brothers.
I was speaking over there to the Beaumont A&M Club, noted for their enthusiasm and their loyalty, and the president was mentioning, this is when women were just here,
And the president mentioned and reminded the group that his wife, after World War II, had been a summer school student here for three summers, and she had earned 18 hours.
And he got a great laugh by repeating what she had said.
She said, I only got 18 hours of credit, but I have more grade points than all the Kokonos brothers combined.
And the Beaumont audience chuckled.
And then he added, but I remember a reporter asking their father how he felt about having, and I think it was six sons on active duty.
And he said, I feel very proud, and I wish I had six more sons so that they, too, could serve this country.
They're a famous family.
Oh, my, yes.
Let's see.
Next to last question.

Let's make believe that someone gives you a check for $1 million, and there's only one requirement with the gift, that you pass that million dollars on to Texas A&M, but you can decide what use would be made for the money.
If you had a million dollars to give to Texas A&M, what would you want them to do with it?
What would be your favorite purpose?
Well, in some way, I would want it to go to the individuals who attend or want to attend.
That would be scholarships for students.
And then at the same level, you would want it for
not scholarships now, but for the academic leaders to influence the students in the ways.
Buildings, fees can build buildings, but you've got to put it into the person.
And it would depend upon
which side needs the greater emphasis.
And I imagine that A&M, they have a lot of scholarship, but probably it should come from, I mean to, and I guess they are too doing that, would be provide teaching chairs,
Last question.
Last question.
What feelings do you hold in your heart now for Texas A&M?
Well, I think it's the same that every A&M graduate has, that it's probably the only school in the country that really means something.
and that you try to repay and you never forget the training you had.
I believe that my academic model, my completed one, is very broad, but I don't doubt that the training, the education that I got at A&M was the basis for what I've been able to produce since.
Let's quit there.
